'''Kameido Sengen Shrine''' (亀戸浅間神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Kameido, Kōtō, Tokyo|ja|亀戸|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kōtō, Tokyo|ja|江東区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Editorial Committee, *Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten 13 Tokyo*, Kadokawa Shoten, 1978, p. 842.</ref> It is one of the many {{ill|Sengen shrines|ja|浅間神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} dedicated to the worship of Mount Fuji.

== Enshrined Deity ==
The shrine is dedicated to '''{{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶比売命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''', the guardian deity of Mount Fuji.<ref>[https://www.sengen.or.jp/%e3%81%94%e7%a5%ad%e7%a5%9e%e3%81%a8%e7%94%b1%e7%b7%92/ Enshrined Deity and History] - Official Website</ref>  

She is widely revered as a deity of good fortune, matchmaking, safe childbirth, and child-rearing.

== History ==
The shrine was established in {{ill|Daiei 7|ja|大永7th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1527). During the peak of {{ill|Fuji faith|ja|富士信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, local villagers invited Ganroji Motonaga to enshrine the protective deity of Mount Fuji, '''Konohanasakuya-hime''', establishing the shrine on '''Kōgai Mound'''.

The current shrine building survived the destruction of the {{ill|Great Tokyo Air Raid|ja|東京大空襲|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 1945, earning a reputation among locals as a protector against fire disasters.

Within the shrine grounds stands the '''Fuji Sengen, Kameido Tenjin, Roku Amida, and Asakusa Road Guidepost''', an artifact erected in 1601 (Kyōwa 1). This guidepost is registered as a tangible cultural property by {{ill|Kōtō City|ja|江東区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref> [https://www.city.koto.lg.jp/103020/bunkasports/bunka/shuppanbutsu/documents/sitabun249.pdf Kameido Sengen Shrine Guidepost] - Kōtō City Official Website</ref>

